goals.rationale: This helps to identify the most common origin airports and any potential patterns or trends in the data.

goals.question: What is the distribution of flights by destination airport?
goals.rationale: This helps to identify the most common destination airports and any potential patterns or trends in the data.

goals.rationale: This helps to identify any correlation between flight delay and distance, and whether longer flights tend to have more delays.

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    data['delay'].plot.hist(bins=20)
    plt.xlabel('Delay (minutes)')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of flight delays?')
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        plt.gca().xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    plt.boxplot(data['distance'])
    plt.ylabel('Distance (miles)')
    median_distance = data['distance'].median()
    plt.axhline(y=median_distance, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Median Distance: {median_distance:.2f}')
    plt.legend()
    plt.title("What is the average distance of flights?")
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()

import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import matplotlib.ticker as ticker

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    plt.figure(figsize=(6, 6))
    
    data['date'] = pd.to_datetime(data['date'], errors='ignore')
    origin_counts = data['origin'].value_counts()
    
    ax = origin_counts.plot(kind='bar')
    
    if len(plt.xticks()[0]) > 20:
        ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(ticker.MaxNLocator(20))
    
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title("What is the distribution of flights by origin airport?")
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
chart.show()
